12:55.441 --> 12:57.735
And I need your help

12:57.819 --> 12:59.404
getting Sasha
to listen to reason.

12:59.487 --> 13:01.656
I'll be 21 next month.

13:01.739 --> 13:03.574
I should be able
to control my own money.

13:03.658 --> 13:04.993
Why would he keep
your mother's money?

13:05.076 --> 13:06.536
He doesn't need it.

13:07.453 --> 13:09.163
[laughs softly]

13:09.247 --> 13:10.415
It's not about the money, Helen.

13:10.498 --> 13:13.501
It's about control.

13:13.584 --> 13:16.379
I mean, control me, and
he controls the story I tell.

13:16.462 --> 13:17.797
It's all about his image.

13:17.880 --> 13:19.424
That's the only thing
he actually cares about.

13:19.507 --> 13:21.926
[knocking on window]

13:24.554 --> 13:26.347
Oh, fuck. I've got to get back.

13:26.431 --> 13:28.308
I can't lose this job.

13:28.391 --> 13:30.143
Look, can you just
talk to him for me?

13:30.226 --> 13:32.395
Please?

13:32.478 --> 13:34.605
Will you help me?

13:35.481 --> 13:37.400
I don't know.

13:37.483 --> 13:39.110
I'll think about it.

13:42.363 --> 13:43.656
<i>♪ gentle music ♪</i>

13:43.740 --> 13:44.115
<i>♪♪♪</i>

13:51.456 --> 13:52.582
Hey. You look great.
Do you feel better?

13:52.665 --> 13:56.252
‐Uh, Mariel's here.
‐Who?

13:56.335 --> 13:57.211
Mariel, my social worker.

13:57.295 --> 13:59.464
Oh.

13:59.547 --> 14:01.132
‐Come in.
‐Oh, okay.

14:08.306 --> 14:09.599
Can I get you anything, Mariel?

14:09.682 --> 14:11.142
Tea or biscuits or...?

14:11.225 --> 14:12.435
No, thanks.

14:12.518 --> 14:14.645
I'm all right.

14:16.064 --> 14:17.398
There...

14:17.482 --> 14:18.566
we go. Okay.

14:18.649 --> 14:20.526
Where are you from?

14:20.610 --> 14:23.196
Los Angeles,
born and raised.

14:23.279 --> 14:25.114
Oh, me, too!
California girls!

14:25.198 --> 14:29.243
Do you have any relatives
close by that you can rely on?

14:29.327 --> 14:31.412
Uh, yes.
My‐my mother is close by.

14:31.496 --> 14:32.371
Would you like some cheese?

14:32.455 --> 14:34.707
[Mariel] Uh, what is
your mother's name?

14:34.791 --> 14:37.418
Her name is, um, Adeline Taylor.

14:37.502 --> 14:39.378
[Mariel] And your mother
lives in Los Angeles?

14:39.462 --> 14:42.381
[Sierra] Uh, her‐her primary
residence is Los Angeles, yes.

14:42.465 --> 14:43.925
‐Um, but she's an actress...
‐[Eddie crying]

14:44.008 --> 14:46.344
...so she moves around a lot‐‐
Hey, hey, hey.

14:46.427 --> 14:47.512
[Mariel]
"Primary residence."

14:47.595 --> 14:48.888
Does that mean
she has multiple homes?

14:48.971 --> 14:50.181
It's okay. Yes.

14:50.264 --> 14:51.682
Yeah. Oh, my gosh.

14:51.766 --> 14:53.601
I'm so sorry about the racket.

14:53.684 --> 14:55.478
I totally forgot about
Eddie's sweet potatoes.

14:55.561 --> 14:58.397
I make all of his food
from scratch.

14:58.481 --> 14:59.357
It's okay. Just one sec.

14:59.440 --> 15:01.609
Okay. Okay...

15:01.692 --> 15:04.112
Ooh. Ooh, ooh, ooh.

15:04.195 --> 15:05.696
‐Whoa.
‐Hi.

15:05.780 --> 15:07.573
You have the instincts
of a panther, Helen.

15:07.657 --> 15:09.534
Lucky you were there.

15:09.617 --> 15:11.494
A‐Are you leaving already?

15:11.577 --> 15:13.579
Yes, I‐I think I have
everything I need.

15:13.663 --> 15:15.456
You don't want to ask me
some more questions, or...

15:15.540 --> 15:16.707
Have a nice day.

15:16.791 --> 15:19.961
<i>♪ slow, somber music ♪</i>

15:20.044 --> 15:20.294
[Eddie cries]

15:20.378 --> 15:22.880
Um...

15:22.964 --> 15:24.590
‐It's okay. Ooh.
‐Whoopsie.

15:24.674 --> 15:26.968
H‐Hang on, hang on one second.

15:28.094 --> 15:29.512
Uh, excuse me.

15:29.595 --> 15:32.390
Ma'am, um, you're, uh...

15:32.473 --> 15:35.393
Mariel, um, can you tell me
what the next steps are?

15:35.476 --> 15:37.770
I'm sorry, I can't share that
with anyone but Ms. James.

15:37.854 --> 15:40.314
Okay, but hypothetically,
if it was an investigation

15:40.398 --> 15:43.067
like Sierra's, what‐what‐what
would the next...

15:43.151 --> 15:45.653
Hypothetically, if the subject
of an investigation is found

15:45.736 --> 15:48.698
to be an unfit parent, the
subject's child would be removed

15:48.781 --> 15:50.533
from the home
and placed with the next of kin.

15:50.616 --> 15:52.827
Like her mother?

15:52.910 --> 15:55.204
I really can't talk
about this anymore.

15:57.748 --> 15:59.458
[car door opens, closes]

15:59.542 --> 16:03.004
[engine starts]

16:03.087 --> 16:04.881
‐[crying]
‐[Helen] Sierra.

16:04.964 --> 16:08.676
‐Sierra, it's okay.
‐It's not. It's not.

16:08.759 --> 16:11.012
It's not.
I can't do anything right.

16:11.095 --> 16:12.638
‐I'm gonna end up killing him.
‐Oh, no, you're not.

16:12.722 --> 16:15.183
No, you're not.

16:15.266 --> 16:19.353
It was one mistake. I mean,
this‐this period is‐is...

16:19.437 --> 16:21.063
it's an adjustment.

16:21.147 --> 16:22.356
And all mothers
make mistakes.

16:22.440 --> 16:23.858
No, you don't understand.

16:23.941 --> 16:27.069
I‐I can't get out of bed
in the morning.

16:27.153 --> 16:30.865
I just lay there
staring at the ceiling and I...

16:30.948 --> 16:34.202
I can't stop thinking,
I can't stop thinking about...

16:34.285 --> 16:37.079
hurting myself, and I just
want to leave him somewhere

16:37.163 --> 16:39.040
so that somebody
will find him and,

16:39.123 --> 16:41.626
and I think they should just
take him away from me now

16:41.709 --> 16:43.628
so that he doesn't
have to remember me.

16:43.711 --> 16:45.046
Oh, no.
[Helen shushes]

16:45.129 --> 16:47.048
Oh, God. Sierra.

16:49.717 --> 16:51.093
Listen to me.

16:51.177 --> 16:52.845
‐Will you listen to me?
‐Mm‐hmm.

16:52.929 --> 16:54.722
I think that you need
some help, okay?

16:54.805 --> 16:56.265
[sniffles]

16:56.349 --> 16:59.644
All right? You're not equipped
to do this on your own.

17:02.480 --> 17:05.273
How come everybody
can do this but me?

17:09.819 --> 17:14.282
I don't think that you should
be alone right now. Hmm?

17:14.367 --> 17:16.911
So why don't you and Eddie come
stay with me for a while? Hmm?

17:16.993 --> 17:18.871
‐Okay.
‐Okay.

17:18.954 --> 17:19.872
Thank you.

17:19.955 --> 17:21.123
We'll get you
some help.

17:24.542 --> 17:26.628
[babbles]

17:29.507 --> 17:30.675
[suitcase wheels rolling]

17:33.010 --> 17:35.304
Surprise!

17:35.388 --> 17:36.597
Oh, Jesus Christ, wow.

17:36.681 --> 17:39.141
‐Hey. [laughs]
‐Hey. How you doing?

17:39.225 --> 17:41.227
I thought you were
in the Sahara?

17:41.310 --> 17:43.104
‐Or something...
‐Well, production got shut down.

17:43.187 --> 17:44.897
I mean, uh,
civil unrest

17:44.981 --> 17:46.274
in Chad or something.

17:46.357 --> 17:47.441
Don't know. Whatever.
Doesn't matter.

17:47.525 --> 17:48.442
Can you pack a quick bag?

17:48.526 --> 17:51.237
Uh, we've got a jet waiting
for us at Van Nuys

17:51.320 --> 17:53.614
and a reservation at
the French Laundry in two hours.

17:53.698 --> 17:55.199
Hi. How are you?

17:55.283 --> 17:56.200
Hi.

17:56.284 --> 17:58.786
I‐I can't go to San Francisco.

17:58.869 --> 18:01.122
I mean, my kids are in there.
They're making me dinner.

18:01.205 --> 18:02.164
What the fuck do you mean?

18:02.248 --> 18:04.959
Helen, I flew 15 hours
to surprise you.

18:05.042 --> 18:07.003
Have you got any idea how hard
it is to get a‐a charter

18:07.086 --> 18:08.963
out of Chad during civil war?

18:09.046 --> 18:10.298
‐No.
‐Well, it's hard.

18:13.259 --> 18:15.761
I'm sorry, I can't.
I mean, I just...

18:15.845 --> 18:17.888
I can't. Sorry.

18:17.972 --> 18:19.682
[sighs]
Well, whatever.

18:19.765 --> 18:20.975
You just take these, then.

18:21.058 --> 18:23.686
Uh, it was supposed to say
"happy birthday,"

18:23.769 --> 18:24.437
but, uh, somehow
my assistant fucked up.

18:24.520 --> 18:25.688
I mean, you're‐you're welcome

18:25.771 --> 18:27.023
to come in and join us.

18:27.106 --> 18:29.233
Um, I mean, it's
no French Laundry,

18:29.317 --> 18:31.235
and‐and we'll be
with my kids and...

18:31.319 --> 18:31.694
But...

18:31.777 --> 18:34.530
[Sasha]
Yeah.

18:34.614 --> 18:36.240
Love to.

18:36.324 --> 18:37.450
Yeah.

18:37.867 --> 18:41.120
Okay, cool.

18:42.163 --> 18:44.332
[Sasha]
Um, you know, I picked up

18:44.415 --> 18:47.335
a few tricks when I played
a chef some years back.

18:47.418 --> 18:48.794
‐Do you want me to take over?
‐I'm good.

18:48.878 --> 18:51.714
This is my dad's recipe.

18:51.797 --> 18:53.424
Oh. Your dad's.

18:56.385 --> 19:00.056
Mmm. Stacey, that's an awful lot
of sauce, isn't it?

19:00.139 --> 19:01.891
Nope, it's just right.

19:01.974 --> 19:03.184
[Helen]
Sasha.

19:03.267 --> 19:03.601
Let her do it.

19:03.684 --> 19:06.312
Yeah, sure.

19:06.395 --> 19:07.396
Sorry. Just trying to help.

19:11.067 --> 19:12.526
Are you sure you're all right?

19:12.610 --> 19:14.570
[Trevor]
Oh, uh, Mom hates her birthday.

19:14.654 --> 19:16.030
Yep, even when we were kids,

19:16.113 --> 19:18.282
she wouldn't let us get her

19:18.366 --> 19:19.033
a cake.

19:19.116 --> 19:21.452
My dad would make
a lasagna,

19:21.535 --> 19:24.246
stick a candle in it,
and that'd be it.

19:24.330 --> 19:25.498
Birthday finito.

19:26.123 --> 19:28.709
What a shock you left him.

19:30.795 --> 19:31.837
I didn't, actually. He left me.

19:31.921 --> 19:34.006
[Sierra]
Hello again.

19:34.090 --> 19:35.383
[Sasha]
Hi.

19:35.466 --> 19:36.884
How's your baby?

19:36.967 --> 19:39.553
Uh, he's asleep. Thank God.

19:39.637 --> 19:41.263
[Sasha] See,
that's why I never had kids.

19:41.347 --> 19:45.351
I'm just absolutely useless
without my sleep.

19:46.644 --> 19:48.562
[Stacey]
<i>So,</i>

19:48.646 --> 19:49.647
it's set in the future.

19:49.730 --> 19:51.399
Two astronauts meet by chance

19:51.482 --> 19:53.401
on the International
Space Station.

19:53.484 --> 19:56.946
They fall desperately in love,
but their love is doomed

19:57.029 --> 19:59.990
because they're being sent off
on two different missions

20:00.074 --> 20:02.451
in opposite directions
deep in the bowels of space.

20:02.535 --> 20:04.787
Ooh.

20:04.870 --> 20:07.873
Quite the little tragedian,
isn't she?

20:07.957 --> 20:10.084
I wasn't finished.

20:10.167 --> 20:12.044
Anyways, they try
to forget each other.

20:12.128 --> 20:15.214
They build
completely new lives

20:15.297 --> 20:17.758
with new people.
But it hurts, you know?

20:17.842 --> 20:20.594
Because deep down, they
secretly still love each other.

20:20.678 --> 20:24.265
Until one day,
they run into each other again

20:24.348 --> 20:26.726
on the opposite side
of the galaxy.

20:26.809 --> 20:29.228
Out in space?

20:29.311 --> 20:30.771
That's very convenient,
isn't it?

20:30.855 --> 20:31.856
[Stacey]
Because all this time

20:31.939 --> 20:34.608
they thought they were
moving away from each other,

20:34.692 --> 20:36.235
they were actually in orbit.

20:36.318 --> 20:40.072
They were always meant
to meet again.

20:40.156 --> 20:43.701
<i>♪ slow, gentle music ♪</i>

20:43.784 --> 20:45.995
I need more wine.

20:49.039 --> 20:51.792
I think it's
a very beautiful story, Stacey.

20:51.876 --> 20:54.086
Thanks.

20:54.170 --> 20:56.630
[knocking at door]

20:57.757 --> 21:01.302
‐Hi.
‐Hi.

21:01.385 --> 21:02.720
‐Is Sierra here?
‐Um...

21:02.803 --> 21:04.054
‐Hi, babe.
‐[Sierra] Mom?

21:04.138 --> 21:05.264
I'm so sorry
to just come over like this,

21:05.347 --> 21:08.309
but you're not answering
your phone,

21:08.392 --> 21:10.853
and this Mariel woman
keeps calling me.

21:10.936 --> 21:12.480
She says she's
your social worker?

21:12.563 --> 21:13.981
Hi, I'm Helen.

21:14.064 --> 21:15.441
‐I'm her neighbor.
‐Oh, you're the neighbor.

21:15.524 --> 21:15.900
‐Yeah. Hi.
‐Right, right. Hi.

21:15.983 --> 21:17.985
Adeline Taylor.

21:18.068 --> 21:19.653
‐It's so nice to meet you.
‐Nice to meet you.

21:19.737 --> 21:20.946
Sweetie, we got to go.
Can you get Eddie?

21:21.030 --> 21:22.698
Um, where are we going?

21:22.782 --> 21:25.367
Um, well,

21:25.451 --> 21:26.368
first, we're gonna
go back to my house.

21:26.452 --> 21:29.830
And I got a terrific
baby nurse for Eddie.

21:29.914 --> 21:30.831
And Dr. Miller says
he can take you tonight.

21:30.915 --> 21:33.667
No. Mom, please, I
don't want to go there.

21:33.751 --> 21:36.378
Honey, he's doing us
a tremendous favor,

21:36.462 --> 21:38.881
and it's all gonna be
very private, which is good,

21:38.964 --> 21:39.548
because if the press
gets ahold of this,

21:39.632 --> 21:41.175
they will have a field day.

21:41.258 --> 21:42.718
[Sierra]
Mom, nobody even knows who I am.

21:42.802 --> 21:45.429
[Adeline] Of course they do,
sweetheart, because they know

21:45.513 --> 21:47.056
who I am.

21:47.139 --> 21:50.226
But if we get ahead of this,
we can control it.

21:50.309 --> 21:53.312
All right?
But we need to go tonight.

21:53.395 --> 21:55.523
Adeline?

21:55.606 --> 21:58.859
‐Sasha Mann?
‐What the fuck

21:58.943 --> 21:59.610
are you doing here?

22:01.987 --> 22:03.948
Sierra's my daughter.

22:04.031 --> 22:05.825
[Sasha]
Fuck, no way.

22:05.908 --> 22:07.034
You're, like, you're 35.

22:07.117 --> 22:08.285
[Adeline]
I love you.

22:08.369 --> 22:09.203
Oh, what are you
doing here?

22:09.286 --> 22:12.331
Well, I'm, um...
Hey, I'm, uh...

22:12.414 --> 22:14.250
‐I'm with, um...
‐Helen.

22:14.333 --> 22:15.501
‐I'm with Helen.
‐Oh, thank God.

22:15.584 --> 22:16.043
For a second,
thought you were... [laughs]

22:16.126 --> 22:18.879
Well, okay, Cupid.

22:18.963 --> 22:20.381
Your style's changing a bit.

22:20.464 --> 22:22.424
[Sasha] Hey, I haven't
seen you since, like...

22:22.508 --> 22:23.384
Well, that press junket in
Budapest, for fuck's sake.

22:23.467 --> 22:25.052
What are... What is
she talking about?

22:25.135 --> 22:27.847
Um, she wants
to institutionalize me.

22:27.930 --> 22:30.558
‐What?
‐Yeah, Dr. Miller is, um...

22:30.641 --> 22:32.142
He works at a psych ward.

22:32.226 --> 22:33.602
She, um, she put me in there

22:33.686 --> 22:34.562
when I was a teenager.

22:34.645 --> 22:37.731
[Sasha] [bad accent]
"The sun is rising.

22:37.815 --> 22:39.984
You have no dreams.
Your life is over.

22:40.067 --> 22:42.278
Action!"

22:42.361 --> 22:44.613
‐It's so good to see you.
‐[Sasha] So good to see you.

22:45.739 --> 22:47.950
Sierra, honey,
we really got to go.

22:48.033 --> 22:49.243
<i>♪ quiet, tense music ♪</i>

22:49.326 --> 22:51.412
Honey?

22:51.495 --> 22:53.080
Yeah, I think...

22:53.163 --> 22:54.415
I know you've been away
for a few months,

22:54.498 --> 22:56.584
but I live next
door, and we spend

22:56.667 --> 22:59.295
quite a bit of time
together, and I think...

22:59.378 --> 23:03.632
Sierra is suffering
from postpartum depression.

23:03.716 --> 23:05.426
Are you a doctor?

23:05.509 --> 23:07.136
No.

23:07.219 --> 23:08.762
[chuckles]
That's funny,

23:08.846 --> 23:10.139
because you sounded
like a doctor.

23:10.222 --> 23:12.683
Yeah, I just think
she needs some childcare.

23:12.766 --> 23:14.101
And a therapist.

23:14.184 --> 23:16.103
I don't think she needs
to be institutionalized.

23:16.186 --> 23:17.855
[Adeline]
Institutionalized? I mean,

23:17.938 --> 23:19.189
it's called rehab.

23:20.357 --> 23:22.276
If she's clean, we'll leave.

23:22.359 --> 23:24.403
If she's not,
it's the best place for her.

23:24.486 --> 23:26.780
Helen, perhaps we should
stay out of this. I mean,

23:26.864 --> 23:29.283
let the ladies sort it
themselves. It's not really...

23:29.366 --> 23:30.659
It's none
of our business, is it?

23:30.743 --> 23:32.494
Perhaps <i>you</i> should
stay out of this.

23:35.205 --> 23:39.126
Um...
[clicks tongue]

23:39.209 --> 23:42.630
Do you mind if I just talk to my
daughter privately for a moment?

23:55.142 --> 23:56.518
[Sasha]
Look,

23:56.602 --> 23:58.145
all I'm saying
is that this is

23:58.228 --> 23:59.396
kind of your Achilles'
heel, isn't it?

23:59.480 --> 24:00.898
I wish you would stop trying

24:00.981 --> 24:02.858
to turn me wanting
to help people into a pathology.

24:02.942 --> 24:05.069
Helen, her mother
is a movie star.

24:05.152 --> 24:07.112
She's got all the money
and resources in the world.

24:07.196 --> 24:08.489
Well, I know this might be hard
for you to believe,

24:08.572 --> 24:11.700
but sometimes people
need more than money

24:11.784 --> 24:13.994
‐thrown at their problems.
‐I just think you fill your life

24:14.078 --> 24:15.746
with other people's
problems in order to avoid

24:15.829 --> 24:17.247
addressing your own.
That's all I'm saying.

24:17.331 --> 24:19.458
Do you think this is fun for me?

24:19.541 --> 24:21.543
Spending all this time
with the woman

24:21.627 --> 24:25.047
my boyfriend cheated on me with
and their baby?

24:25.130 --> 24:26.048
Then why do you do it?

24:26.131 --> 24:27.716
Because she needs help.

24:27.800 --> 24:29.510
She's barely hanging on.

24:29.593 --> 24:31.178
Her mother is a psychopath.

24:31.261 --> 24:33.931
I've tried to hate her.
Believe me.

24:34.014 --> 24:35.224
But I c... I can't.

24:35.307 --> 24:35.933
She's just... She's too...

24:36.016 --> 24:38.894
pathetic to hate.

24:38.978 --> 24:40.396
Perhaps you do it

24:40.479 --> 24:42.272
because you hate her.

24:42.356 --> 24:44.233
What?

24:44.316 --> 24:46.443
Helen, people will go
to crazy lengths

24:46.527 --> 24:48.529
to avoid feeling that feeling.

24:48.612 --> 24:51.407
All right, well...

24:51.490 --> 24:52.241
Speaking of people you hate,

24:52.324 --> 24:55.035
guess who
I had coffee with today.

24:56.120 --> 24:57.454
Christianna.

24:57.538 --> 24:58.038
Christianna. Why?

24:58.122 --> 25:00.541
She reached out to me.

25:00.624 --> 25:03.043
But how'd she find you?

25:03.127 --> 25:03.877
‐What does it matter?
‐Well,

25:03.961 --> 25:04.837
you're kind of hard
to track down.

25:04.920 --> 25:06.839
You're not on social media
or anything.

25:06.922 --> 25:08.549
Why don't you want me
to talk to her?

25:08.632 --> 25:09.633
Because why would you?

25:09.717 --> 25:11.093
She asked me for help
getting through to you.

25:11.176 --> 25:14.013
She says the money's hers.

25:14.096 --> 25:15.931
Oh. She told you
about Lily's trust, did she?

25:16.015 --> 25:18.434
‐Yeah.
‐Mm‐hmm.

25:18.517 --> 25:20.394
Did she tell you
she's writing a book?

25:20.477 --> 25:21.729
I think so.

25:21.812 --> 25:23.522
Book about me?

25:24.481 --> 25:25.566
No.

25:25.649 --> 25:26.608
Mm‐hmm.

25:26.692 --> 25:29.945
Listen, I know
she can be very convincing,

25:30.029 --> 25:31.530
but she's lying.

25:31.613 --> 25:33.949
She's full of
horseshit. I mean,

25:34.033 --> 25:36.368
Lily and I loved each other,
Helen.

25:36.452 --> 25:38.454
I met her
when Christianna was five,

25:38.537 --> 25:39.621
and I helped raise her.

25:39.705 --> 25:41.123
We were a family.

25:41.206 --> 25:42.499
But when Christianna
became a teenager,

25:42.583 --> 25:45.335
she got this
asshole boyfriend

25:45.419 --> 25:47.087
that convinced her
to break into Lily's phone

25:47.171 --> 25:49.465
and steal these photos
of me and Lily naked,

25:49.548 --> 25:51.425
and Christianna went
and sold them.

25:51.508 --> 25:53.427
After that, Lily
put a stipulation

25:53.510 --> 25:54.970
in Christianna's trust

25:55.054 --> 25:56.263
that if she wanted

25:56.346 --> 25:58.015
her grandparents' money
when she was an adult,

25:58.098 --> 26:00.392
she could not disparage
me or Lily publicly.

26:00.476 --> 26:04.605
‐And has she?
‐No, not yet.

26:04.688 --> 26:07.399
But she's written
this tell‐all book,

26:07.483 --> 26:09.151
and she wants to publish it.

26:09.234 --> 26:12.279
She gets her inheritance in full
when she's 25,

26:12.362 --> 26:13.822
which gives me four years
to change her mind.

26:15.741 --> 26:16.950
I mean, why...

26:17.034 --> 26:18.744
why did Lily put you
in charge of her trust?

26:18.827 --> 26:21.497
Because she trusted me, Helen.

26:21.580 --> 26:23.707
Christianna says
you never send the checks.

26:23.791 --> 26:25.000
Mm‐hmm, because I don't
know where she lives.

26:25.084 --> 26:26.460
She's a grifter.

26:26.543 --> 26:28.712
She moves around
every six months.

26:28.796 --> 26:30.297
You know, why don't you
just give her the money

26:30.380 --> 26:32.299
and let her publish the book
if you have nothing to hide?

26:32.382 --> 26:33.717
For fuck's sake!

26:33.801 --> 26:35.803
That would ruin my career.

26:35.886 --> 26:38.597
I've worked too hard
for too long

26:38.680 --> 26:40.099
to throw my whole life away

26:40.182 --> 26:41.433
just because Christianna
is angry that her mother died

26:41.517 --> 26:43.852
and wants to blame it
on somebody.

26:43.936 --> 26:46.688
She says you got her mother
hooked on drugs.

26:46.772 --> 26:47.397
Are you f...

26:47.481 --> 26:50.234
Are you fucking kidding me?

26:50.317 --> 26:52.694
<i>♪ slow, somber music ♪</i>

26:52.778 --> 26:54.196
<i>♪♪♪</i>

26:54.279 --> 26:55.823
[exhales]

26:57.825 --> 27:01.954
Your ex‐husband did a truly
amazing job of fucking you over.

27:02.037 --> 27:04.623
But if you don't
trust me by now,

27:04.706 --> 27:06.875
I don't know
what the fuck to tell you.

27:10.504 --> 27:11.880
[door slides open]

27:13.674 --> 27:15.342
[door slides closed]

27:15.425 --> 27:16.718
[Adeline]
Sierra, honey,

27:16.802 --> 27:18.929
go get Eddie.
We're really late.

27:19.012 --> 27:19.680
What's going on?

27:19.763 --> 27:22.724
I'm gonna go
and see Dr. Miller,

27:22.808 --> 27:26.603
and my mom is gonna
take, uh, care of Eddie

27:26.687 --> 27:28.063
while I get some help.

27:30.440 --> 27:33.694
Oh, Sierra, there has to be
some other option.

27:33.777 --> 27:36.738
No, I don't think so.

27:36.822 --> 27:38.365
What if I take him?

27:38.448 --> 27:40.284
Helen.

27:40.367 --> 27:41.577
What?

27:41.660 --> 27:43.120
You can stay here
as long as you like,

27:43.203 --> 27:46.206
and I'll try to find someone
to come here and help you.

27:46.290 --> 27:47.583
What are you doing?

27:47.666 --> 27:49.418
She's his mother.
I don't think

27:49.501 --> 27:51.169
they should be
separated right now.

27:51.253 --> 27:53.714
[exhales]

27:53.797 --> 27:54.840
Hey, I'm beat.

27:54.923 --> 27:56.592
I've been awake for 24 hours,

27:56.675 --> 27:59.386
so if you'll excuse me.

27:59.469 --> 28:01.263
‐Um, Adeline,
wonderful to see you.
‐[Adeline] Mwah!

28:01.346 --> 28:03.807
‐Call me.
‐I will.

28:03.891 --> 28:06.018
‐We'll have lunch or something.
‐We will. Bye.

28:08.395 --> 28:11.231
[Adeline sighs]

28:11.315 --> 28:14.359
I‐I can tell you care
about my daughter.

28:14.443 --> 28:17.237
Many people do.

28:17.321 --> 28:19.489
She has a knack
for finding those people

28:19.573 --> 28:22.159
who want to save her,

28:22.242 --> 28:24.161
but then they just end up
enabling her addictions

28:24.244 --> 28:25.621
and laziness

28:25.704 --> 28:28.916
and her refusal
to accept any responsibility

28:28.999 --> 28:30.167
for her life.

28:30.250 --> 28:32.794
Excuse me?

28:32.878 --> 28:35.547
Oh, I'm sorry.
I'm not saying you're...

28:35.631 --> 28:37.174
one of those people.

28:37.257 --> 28:38.300
I‐I don't know you.

28:38.383 --> 28:42.512
But I do know my daughter.

28:43.597 --> 28:47.184
She's sweet and beautiful,

28:47.267 --> 28:50.771
but she's also a fuckup,
and she needs professional help.

28:50.854 --> 28:53.774
She doesn't need another...

28:53.857 --> 28:57.277
well‐intentioned hanger‐on.

28:57.361 --> 29:00.072
What the fuck is wrong with you?

29:02.407 --> 29:04.743
Why do you think
I'm such a fuckup, Mom?

29:04.826 --> 29:06.912
Did you know
that until I met Helen,

29:06.995 --> 29:08.705
I didn't even realize
there were people in the world

29:08.789 --> 29:12.125
who loved their kids
just for being alive?

29:12.209 --> 29:14.962
Just because
they fucking existed?

29:15.045 --> 29:17.005
You should see her
with her kids.

29:17.089 --> 29:17.464
She's amazing.

29:17.547 --> 29:18.507
She loves them.

29:18.590 --> 29:21.802
She just fucking loves them.

29:21.885 --> 29:24.054
They can fuck up or,
or say something stupid

29:24.137 --> 29:26.264
and it's like
she doesn't even notice.

29:26.348 --> 29:29.768
If I ever had
a‐a pimple on my face,

29:29.851 --> 29:30.811
you would tell me
you couldn't even look at me.

29:30.894 --> 29:32.562
I stopped eating
because you said

29:32.646 --> 29:34.648
you'd rather have
a dead daughter than a fat one.

29:34.731 --> 29:35.816
I was kidding.

29:35.899 --> 29:37.567
It wasn't fucking funny.

29:38.902 --> 29:39.486
You didn't want
a daughter.

29:39.569 --> 29:41.905
You just wanted a doll

29:41.989 --> 29:44.157
that you could dress up
and parade around

29:44.241 --> 29:45.826
and bring to interviews
when you needed

29:45.909 --> 29:47.411
‐to seem more human.
‐Oh, my God, oh, my God,

29:47.494 --> 29:49.454
oh, my God.
I tried so hard.

29:49.538 --> 29:50.455
My parents were useless.

29:50.539 --> 29:52.582
Rich and famous

29:52.666 --> 29:54.292
‐and useless.
‐Oh, my God.

29:54.376 --> 29:55.335
They had their assistant

29:55.419 --> 29:58.964
take me to get my tonsils out
when I was five.

29:59.047 --> 30:01.550
I did not want that
to be your childhood.

30:01.633 --> 30:04.177
I wanted you with me.

30:04.261 --> 30:07.389
I‐I‐I wanted us to be
in this together.

30:07.472 --> 30:09.474
You know, but I guess
I fucked up.

30:09.558 --> 30:12.394
I‐I pushed you too hard
or I protected you too much.

30:12.477 --> 30:14.271
I don't know.

30:14.354 --> 30:16.189
I think I was just so afraid

30:16.273 --> 30:18.108
of the scrutiny
you were gonna be under

30:18.191 --> 30:21.194
because you were my kid.

30:21.278 --> 30:23.697
It's a scary world,
Sierra.

30:26.116 --> 30:28.493
The only thing
that I'm scared of, Mom,

30:28.577 --> 30:31.246
in the whole world,

30:31.329 --> 30:33.707
the whole entire world...

30:33.790 --> 30:35.876
is you.

30:42.883 --> 30:45.010
How do you two
know each other again?

30:48.472 --> 30:50.140
Don't do that, Mom.

30:50.223 --> 30:52.893
Oh. [sighs] Right.

30:54.227 --> 30:55.729
She...

30:55.812 --> 30:58.231
fucked your dying husband

30:58.315 --> 31:01.526
and then got pregnant
and had his baby?

31:02.861 --> 31:06.114
Well, technically,
he wasn't my husband.

31:06.198 --> 31:08.158
Mm‐hmm.

31:08.241 --> 31:11.203
And you really feel you have
her best interests at heart.

31:13.580 --> 31:16.500
Life is short, Adeline.

31:18.376 --> 31:20.337
Okay.

31:21.046 --> 31:23.423
Sierra, I'll see you tomorrow.

31:23.507 --> 31:26.426
[footsteps retreating]

31:28.678 --> 31:29.763
[exhales]

31:29.846 --> 31:32.724
‐[sighs]
‐[door closes]

31:36.103 --> 31:38.438
Um...

31:38.522 --> 31:39.481
Do you mind if I just go to bed?

31:39.564 --> 31:41.733
I'm... very tired.

31:41.817 --> 31:43.276
Of course.

31:44.402 --> 31:46.446
Happy birthday.

31:46.530 --> 31:48.281
Thank you.

31:58.625 --> 32:01.711
[knocking at door]

32:09.094 --> 32:11.513
Happy birthday.

32:15.517 --> 32:17.978
[Noah] <i>Well, I kind of like
the cover art they chose.</i>

32:18.061 --> 32:18.937
<i>It's, like,</i>

32:19.020 --> 32:20.480
bare trees
in a winter wood.

32:20.564 --> 32:21.565
It's kind of haunting.

32:21.648 --> 32:22.732
It's a beautiful book, Noah.

32:22.816 --> 32:23.984
‐It really is.
‐Thanks.

32:24.067 --> 32:26.069
Thank you. And thank
you for your blurb.

32:26.153 --> 32:28.113
‐I'm really grateful.
‐Ah, I loved reading it.

32:28.196 --> 32:31.700
[sighs] I'm sorry about
your mom, by the way.

32:31.783 --> 32:33.368
That part was true,
wasn't it?

32:33.451 --> 32:34.161
Mm‐hmm.

32:34.244 --> 32:36.705
I had no idea
back at school.

32:36.788 --> 32:38.665
Well, nobody did.

32:38.748 --> 32:40.208
You know what I find
sort of interesting,

32:40.292 --> 32:42.335
now that I'm getting older?

32:42.419 --> 32:44.921
All those people I thought were
so cool back when I was young?

32:45.005 --> 32:47.465
‐Mm‐hmm.
‐Just effortlessly cool...

32:47.549 --> 32:50.135
Those people were
in so much pain.

32:50.218 --> 32:51.678
‐You think?
‐Ah.

32:51.761 --> 32:53.180
To a person.

32:53.263 --> 32:55.015
There's no such thing
as being cool when you're young.

32:55.098 --> 32:56.725
‐[laughs]
‐There's just different degrees

32:56.808 --> 32:59.060
of terrified and how adept
you are at hiding it.

32:59.144 --> 33:01.563
Which is inversely proportional,
in my opinion.

33:01.646 --> 33:03.273
I love you, Ariel.

33:03.356 --> 33:05.066
I love you, too, Noah.

33:07.485 --> 33:09.404
It feels like
things are finally

33:09.487 --> 33:11.823
coming back together
for you, huh?

33:12.866 --> 33:15.035
Hey, you want to get a coffee?

33:15.118 --> 33:16.119
I'm buying.

33:16.203 --> 33:17.245
Sure.

33:22.834 --> 33:25.003
Can I ask you something?

33:26.171 --> 33:27.881
I got a call a couple
of days ago

33:27.964 --> 33:29.758
from a reporter who's doing
this long‐form story

33:29.841 --> 33:32.385
about me and my "resurrection."

33:32.469 --> 33:33.887
Where? For what?

33:33.970 --> 33:34.679
<i>Vanity Fair.</i>

33:34.763 --> 33:36.556
‐Wow.
‐Mm.

33:36.640 --> 33:37.766
No, it's great, but...

33:37.849 --> 33:41.937
she asked me about this, uh,

33:42.020 --> 33:45.023
publicist I had
on the <i>Descent</i> tour...

33:45.106 --> 33:49.527
who, apparently,
has said that I...

33:49.611 --> 33:52.405
I don't know, tried
to seduce her or something.

33:52.489 --> 33:54.157
Tried to seduce her?

33:54.241 --> 33:56.826
Pressured her
into sleeping with me.

33:57.744 --> 33:59.412
That's different.

33:59.496 --> 34:01.581
I know... I know.

34:01.665 --> 34:03.208
I mean, I‐I don't know
what she meant,

34:03.291 --> 34:04.918
but, I mean,
she kind of blindsided me.

34:05.001 --> 34:06.044
What did you say?

34:06.127 --> 34:07.295
Well, I told her it wasn't true.

34:07.379 --> 34:08.420
Which it wasn't.

34:08.505 --> 34:09.547
The opposite, in fact.

34:09.630 --> 34:13.510
I mean, she was throwing herself
at me the whole time.

34:15.762 --> 34:16.846
[chuckles]
What, you don't believe me?

34:16.929 --> 34:18.139
[chuckles]
I didn't say that.

34:18.223 --> 34:19.808
But you don't.

34:19.891 --> 34:22.143
I'm telling you, she was,
she was pretty aggressive.

34:22.226 --> 34:25.605
Okay, so what
are you worried about?

34:25.688 --> 34:27.815
Well, I don't know.
Nothing, I guess.

34:27.899 --> 34:30.777
It's probably fine.

34:30.860 --> 34:32.362
The reporter didn't seem
that interested, actually.

34:32.445 --> 34:36.658
She was probably
just doing due diligence, but...

34:38.034 --> 34:39.536
I mean, this publicist, Eden,

34:39.619 --> 34:41.371
she can't just make shit up
about me, right?

34:41.454 --> 34:44.123
You know you don't have
the best reputation

34:44.206 --> 34:46.001
around this stuff, right?

34:46.083 --> 34:47.835
Ariel, that was in college,
that was 30 years ago.

34:47.918 --> 34:50.255
That's not what
I'm talking about.

34:50.338 --> 34:52.924
I'm talking about
your current reputation, Noah.

34:53.007 --> 34:53.591
In the community.

34:53.675 --> 34:55.719
What community?

34:55.802 --> 34:57.804
The publishing world.

34:57.887 --> 35:00.724
You're seen as something
of a loose cannon.

35:00.807 --> 35:01.349
What?

35:01.433 --> 35:03.560
Why?

35:03.643 --> 35:06.896
Well, you've had a storied past.

35:06.980 --> 35:08.648
You went to prison, after all.

35:08.732 --> 35:10.525
Well, that's just
fucking ridiculous.

35:10.609 --> 35:12.694
I went to prison for my...

35:14.404 --> 35:15.655
For what?

35:15.739 --> 35:17.824
Never mind.

35:17.907 --> 35:19.284
I don't deserve that.

35:19.367 --> 35:22.287
I‐I‐I have
the most boring fucking life.

35:22.370 --> 35:25.040
I work, I write, I see my kids,

35:25.123 --> 35:28.001
and I try to be
a good person, that's it.

35:28.084 --> 35:30.378
I know you do.

35:30.462 --> 35:33.840
But, look...
when you got out of prison,

35:33.923 --> 35:37.093
you were a little bit angry,
right?

35:37.177 --> 35:38.678
A little bit bitter?

35:38.762 --> 35:40.597
Sure. Prison sucks.

35:40.680 --> 35:42.682
Right, well...

35:42.766 --> 35:44.225
Do you remember teaching a class

35:44.309 --> 35:45.977
with a student named Audrey
in it?

35:46.061 --> 35:48.021
Audrey Nelson?

35:48.104 --> 35:50.982
Uh... yeah.

35:51.066 --> 35:53.568
Were you not very nice
to her?

35:55.028 --> 35:56.696
Well, I was as nice
to her as I was

35:56.780 --> 35:58.615
to anyone else
in that class. Why?

35:58.698 --> 36:00.742
She's written a book.

36:00.825 --> 36:01.368
Good for her.

36:01.451 --> 36:03.620
Apparently, you're in it.

36:03.703 --> 36:05.872
Really?

36:05.955 --> 36:08.583
She doesn't name you directly,
but it's a memoir

36:08.667 --> 36:11.961
about her abusive relationship
with an older male professor.

36:12.045 --> 36:14.589
She's going around town,
telling people

36:14.673 --> 36:18.093
that the character
is based on you.

36:18.176 --> 36:20.011
The book is getting
a lot of buzz.

36:20.095 --> 36:22.847
<i>♪ ominous piano music ♪</i>

36:22.931 --> 36:23.682
<i>♪♪♪</i>

36:23.765 --> 36:26.309
[horn honks]

36:37.070 --> 36:38.571
[Harry]
Look, Noah, I can't say

36:38.655 --> 36:40.407
that I am entirely
surprised.

36:40.490 --> 36:42.909
Nowadays, you can't
be too careful.

36:42.992 --> 36:44.911
These accusations are
coming from anywhere.

36:44.994 --> 36:47.288
Luckily, we are prepared.

36:47.372 --> 36:48.790
You're gonna really love Joyce.

36:48.873 --> 36:49.874
She's like the MVP
of our firm these days.

36:49.958 --> 36:52.919
So, how you been otherwise?

36:53.002 --> 36:55.255
Excited for
the <i>Descent</i> premiere?

36:55.338 --> 36:57.090
We are gonna do a rerelease

36:57.173 --> 36:58.007
with Sasha Mann's face
on the cover

36:58.091 --> 37:00.260
to coincide with the opening.

37:00.343 --> 37:01.970
Get you some more moola.

37:02.053 --> 37:02.721
Want to see the cover art?

37:02.804 --> 37:03.930
Not really.

37:04.013 --> 37:06.099
Uh, I'm sure it's fine.

37:07.934 --> 37:10.061
Sit, sit.

37:10.145 --> 37:11.271
‐I'm Joyce.
‐Hey.

37:11.354 --> 37:13.106
I'm Noah.

37:13.189 --> 37:14.315
So...

37:14.399 --> 37:18.570
Harry filled me in
on most of the details.

37:18.653 --> 37:22.115
The reporter is Petra Ranes
from <i>Vanity Fair.</i>

37:22.198 --> 37:23.825
‐Mm‐hmm.
‐And this woman,

37:23.908 --> 37:26.453
uh, Eden Ellery, she used
to work with us, right?

37:26.536 --> 37:29.164
Right, she was our in‐house
publicist about ten years ago.

37:29.247 --> 37:32.167
She left a few years
before you arrived.

37:32.250 --> 37:34.878
Okay.

37:34.961 --> 37:36.921
And this alleged incident
happened over ten years ago?

37:37.005 --> 37:39.132
"Alleged incident"?

37:39.215 --> 37:40.717
‐Nothing happened.
‐[Harry] That's right.

37:40.800 --> 37:42.177
It seems a little convenient,
doesn't it?

37:42.260 --> 37:43.970
Just when he's got a movie

37:44.053 --> 37:45.638
and a new book coming out,
suddenly she remembers

37:45.722 --> 37:49.100
‐being harassed?
‐No, I didn't harass her.

37:49.184 --> 37:50.685
Noah, it's okay.
We're on your side.

37:50.769 --> 37:51.436
[Joyce]
And so you want to know

37:51.519 --> 37:53.146
what to give her as a statement?

37:53.229 --> 37:55.106
He already gave her a statement.

37:57.066 --> 37:58.485
Without talking to anyone?

37:58.568 --> 38:00.069
I didn't know I was supposed to.

38:00.153 --> 38:02.071
Well, what did you say?

38:02.155 --> 38:05.158
Uh, basically, I said no.

38:05.241 --> 38:08.369
Mm. Do you remember
exactly what you said?

38:08.453 --> 38:08.953
Uh...

38:09.037 --> 38:12.040
But you denied it?

38:12.123 --> 38:13.958
‐Yeah.
‐[Harry] Well, we can call

38:14.042 --> 38:15.794
and we can find out
exactly what he said, can't we?

38:15.877 --> 38:17.253
I don't know. We can try,
but she may not give it to us.

38:17.337 --> 38:20.548
Guys, there's no truth
to this story.

38:20.632 --> 38:21.007
None at all?

38:21.090 --> 38:24.844
No. I mean...

38:24.928 --> 38:27.722
I remember
Eden was very flirtatious,

38:27.806 --> 38:30.058
and I think maybe I kissed her

38:30.141 --> 38:31.851
in my hotel room, but...

38:31.935 --> 38:33.686
it was totally consensual.

38:33.770 --> 38:34.979
And you weren't married
at the time.

38:35.063 --> 38:37.816
No, I‐I was married.

38:37.899 --> 38:38.900
I was married to Alison,

38:38.983 --> 38:41.528
but, look, I know I wasn't
the best guy at that time.

38:41.611 --> 38:42.821
I know that.
Everybody knows that.

38:42.904 --> 38:45.240
I mean, so much of what
the <i>Jack Hunter</i> book is about

38:45.323 --> 38:47.992
is me wrestling with who I was
and what I did and why.

38:48.076 --> 38:49.118
But there's a difference
between poor judgment

38:49.202 --> 38:52.121
and being a criminal, right?

38:52.205 --> 38:53.289
[scoffs]
Well...

